#Histogram of the residuals 
hist(Model$residuals)

#qqplot Line
qqnorm(Model$residuals, col= "Blue")
qqline(Model$residuals)

The above two plots 1) Histogram for residuals and 2) qqplot line, shows the residual errors are normally distributed and which satisfies the assumption of linear regression of Normality. It also confirms that distribution is normal, therefore the regression model is fit for the data and R-squared is a good estimator for the model accuracy.

#Question 2b)
#Build a model that uses the number of cylinders (cyl) and the mile per gallon (mpg) values of a car to predict the car Horsepower (hp). 

#Answer
model_hp <- lm(hp~cyl + mpg, data = mtcars)
summary(model_hp)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = hp ~ cyl + mpg, data = mtcars)
## 
## Residuals:
##    Min     1Q Median     3Q    Max 
## -53.72 -22.18 -10.13  14.47 130.73 
## 
## Coefficients:
##             Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)   
## (Intercept)   54.067     86.093   0.628  0.53492   
## cyl           23.979      7.346   3.264  0.00281 **
## mpg           -2.775      2.177  -1.275  0.21253   
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 38.22 on 29 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.7093, Adjusted R-squared:  0.6892 
## F-statistic: 35.37 on 2 and 29 DF,  p-value: 1.663e-08
#I. Using this model, what is the estimated Horse Power of a car with 4 calendar and mpg of 22? 

#Answer
hp_estim <- predict(model_hp,data.frame(cyl = c(4),mpg=c(22)))
hp_estim
##        1 
## 88.93618
#II.    Construct an 85% confidence interval of your answer in the above question. 

#Answer
predict(model_hp,data.frame(cyl = c(4),mpg=c(22)),interval = "prediction",level=0.85)
##        fit      lwr      upr
## 1 88.93618 28.53849 149.3339

#Question 3 b I)
#Imagine two houses that are identical in all aspects, but one bounds the Chas River and the other does not. Which one is more expensive and by how much? 

#Answer
#From the summary of the model, the coefficient for chas1 is 4.58393 
#Based on this regression model chas1 is statistically significant in estimating median house price. The price for house bounds to Chas River would be more expensive than other which does not have. 
#The price of medv = 4.58393 + 49.91868 = $54.50261. The value for which does not have chas river is binary. Therefore, in the model the values of 0 is ignored. 
#Question 3 b II)

ptratio1<-lm(medv~ptratio, data=BostonHousing)
predict(ptratio1,newdata = data.frame(ptratio=15))
##      1 
## 29.987
ptratio2<-lm(medv~ptratio, data=BostonHousing)
predict(ptratio2,newdata = data.frame(ptratio=18))
##        1 
## 23.51547

From the above two ratio, ptration1 with value of 15 is more expensive than ptratio 2 with value of 18. As coefficient of ptratio is negative, smaller the ratio better will be the price. ptratio1 is more expensive than ptratio2 by 6.47153.

#c) Which of the variables are statistically important (i.e. related to the house price)? Hint: use the p-values of the coefficients to answer. 

#Answer
#Based on the P-values of coefficients, all variables (crim, zn, ptratio, and chase1) are statistically important variable. All values are smaller than 0.05. Hence we can reject the nullhypothesis whic means independent variables have effect on target. Lower the value of variable greater will be the house price.

We can see that the variability (sum squared) explained by the crim variable is significantly higher than that of chas variable. Chas variable is a least indicative variable We could guess this as adding the crim, zn, and ptratio, significantly improved the model. Still we can see that a large portion of the variability is unexplained which is 27344.5, that is shown by residuals. The order of importance is crim, ptratio, zn and chas based on the sum squared values.
